2018-12-19.text: You just have to be determined and yes, it sounds radical to put your body through pain to get what you want, but it may be your only option. With that said, you know your body better than anyone else, if you ever need someone to talk to just reach out.

By detoxing from sugar and carbs I started to crave them less and can now eat them in moderation without binging. Yes keto is a lifestyle change be it doesn't have to be permanent. It may be something to consider.
The reason I suggest keto, is because before keto I was addicted to carbs and sugar, and even having them in moderation caused me to crave them, in doing so during moments of weakness I would binge.
To be honest, if I were in your place and had to choose between losing weight to live and my gallbladder, life wins.

Amberlynn, I'm not saying you're wrong, but two different people with two different surgeons were told the same thing. Like I said earlier, your gallbladder is an issue you will most definitely have to deal with at some point. Someone your size doesn't have many options.

That's interesting, I had gallstones after interning in Africa one summer. I went from a high fat American diet fast food and all, to a moderate protein high carb diet, had several gallbladder attacks. Resulted in surgery to remove my gallbladder.

You do have sugar withdrawals and they suck, but once your over it your body starts to crave those healthy fats, and you find that you are more satiated for longer. You will feel so much healthier and better about yourself.
I can attest to that. I lost 25lbs in just under two months on Keto. My hormone levels evened out, my skin is healthier, my asthma has subsided. Plus a ton more health benefits.
I speak from experience. We can all see you spiraling out, some of us really do hope you face reality and start your path to a better life.
Amber you are over 500 lbs at some point you WILL have problems with your gallbladder and you WILL have to have it removed. Your overall health is more important than this one potential issue.

High carb diets trigger insulin which directly causes gallstones. Insulin converts carbs into cholesterol. High protein diets can also trigger insulin and cause gallstones. High fat diets do not cause gallstones unless your carbs are high.

Going on a low fat diet will cause your gallbladder more problems than keto will. When you stop giving your body fat to digest the bile settles and the gallstones start to get stuck, when you keep them moving they're less problematic.
